vents/News/CAWCS/Marble-Bust-of-prolific-Merthyr-scholar-rediscovered.aspx  | title = Marble Bust of prolific Merthyr scholar rediscovered  | year = 2016}}<br />\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stephens, Thomas}}\n[[Category:Welsh literary critics]]\n[[Category:Welsh historians]]\n[[Category:Celtic studies scholars]]\n[[Category:1821 births]]\n[[Category:1875 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century British journalists]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:19th-century historians]]\n[[Category:19th-century British male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Welsh historian (1821\u20131875)}}\n{{Other uses|Thomas Stevens (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Thomas Stephens\n| image              = Thomas Stephens (1821\u20131875).jpg\n| birth_date         = {{birth date |df=y|1821|04|21}}\n| birth_place        = [[Pont Nedd Fechan]], Glamorganshire, Wales\n| death_date         = {{death date and age |df=y|1875|01|04|1821|04|21}}\n| death_place        = [[Merthyr Tydfil]], Glamorganshire, Wales\n| burial_place       = \n| occupation         = [[Apothecary|Chemist and druggist]]\n| known_for          = Welsh historical literature, rigorous critical methods, social reform\n| notable_works      = &bull; ''The Literature of the Kymry'' (1849,1876)<br/>\n&bull; ''Madoc: An Essay on the Discovery of America by Madoc ap Owen Gwynedd in the Twelfth Century'' (1858,1893)<br/>\n&bull; ''Orgraff yr Iaith Gymraeg'' (1859) (an orthography of Welsh)\n}}\n'''Thomas Stephens''' ([[Bardic name]]s: '''Casnodyn, Gwrnerth, Caradawg''') (21 April 1821 \u2013 4 January 1875) was a Welsh historian, [[Literary criticism|literary critic]], and [[Reform movement|social reformer]]. His works include ''The Literature of the Kymry'' (1849,1876), ''Madoc: An Essay on the Discovery of America by Madoc ap Owen Gwynedd in the Twelfth Century'' (1858,1893), and ''Orgraff yr Iaith Gymraeg'' (1859) (an [[orthography]] of [[Welsh language|Welsh]]), as well as a number of prize-winning essays presented at [[eisteddfod]]au between 1840 and 1858. He was the first Welsh historian and literary critic to employ rigorous scientific methods, and is considered to have done more to raise the standards of the National Eisteddfod than any other Welshman of his time. Stephens also figured prominently in efforts to implement social, educational and sanitary reforms both locally in [[Merthyr Tydfil]] and more broadly throughout [[Wales]].\n\n== Life ==\nStephens was born on 21 April 1821 at [[Pont Nedd Fechan]], Glamorganshire, Wales, the son of a boot-maker. In 1835 he was apprenticed as a [[Apothecary|chemist and druggist]] in Merthyr Tydfil and took over the business in 1841. He was also appointed manager of the ''Merthyr Express'' newspaper in 1864.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/oxfordcompaniont00meic/page/562/mode/1up|title=Oxford Companion to the Literature of Wales|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1986|isbn=0-19-211586-3|editor-last=Stephens|editor-first=Meic|location=Oxford|pages=562\u2013563}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://biography.wales/article/s11-STEP-THO-1821|title=Stephens, Thomas (Casnodyn, Gwrnerth, Caradawg; 1821\u20131875), Historian and Social Reformer|last=L\u00f6ffler|first=Marion|date=7 August 2017|website=The National Library of Wales: Dictionary of Welsh Biography|url-status=live|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3434011/3434016/128/|title=Mr Thos. Stephens. Distinguished Welsh Litterateur. Proposed Memorial|date=28 March 1908|work=The Cardiff Times|access-date=11 March 2020|url-status=live|page=5}}</ref>\n\nStephens suffered a series of strokes from 1868.<ref name=\":0\" /> Stephens died on 4 January 1875 in Merthy Tydfil and was buried at [[Cefn-coed-y-cymmer|Cefncoedycymmer]] cemetery.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3076362/3076365/15/|title=Deaths|date=8 January 1875|work=The Merthyr Telegraph|access-date=9 March 2020|url-status=live|page=3}}</ref>\n\n== Writings ==\nStephens began submitting prize-winning essays to [[Eisteddfod|eisteddfodau]] from 1840. His [[Bardic name]]s were Casnodyn, Gwrnerth, and Caradawg. Stephens' most important work, ''The Literature of the Kymry'' (1849, 2nd ed. 1876<ref name=\"Kymry\">{{Cite book|last=Stephens|first=Thomas|url=https://archive.org/details/literatureofkymr00steprich/page/n9/mode/2up|title=The Literature of the Kymry|publisher=Longmans, Green, & Co.|year=1876|editor-last=Evans|editor-first=Sylvan|edition=2nd|location=London}}</ref>), was based on his essay \"The Literature of Wales during the Twelfth and Succeeding Centuries\" which won the Prince of Wales Prize at the 1848 eisteddfod held in [[Abergavenny]]. In this work, Stephens pioneered the use of rigorous methods of literary criticism in the study of medieval Welsh literature.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Stephens,_Thomas_(DNB00)|title=Stephens, Thomas (DNB00): Dictionary of National Biography, 1885\u20131900, Volume 54|last=Thomas|first=Daniel Lleufer|date=n.d.|website=Wikisource|volume=54|url-status=live|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Williams\">{{Cite book|last=Williams|first=B. T.|url=https://archive.org/details/literatureofkymr00steprich/page/n25/mode/2up|title=The Life of Thomas Stephens|publisher=|year=1876|isbn=|location=|pages=xix\u2013xlviii, in Stephens, Thomas (1876). Evans, Sylvan (ed.). ''The Literature of the Kymry'' (2nd ed.). London: Longmans, Green, & Co}}</ref>\n\nStephens' 1858 eisteddfod essay ''Madoc: An Essay on the Discovery of America by Madoc ap Owen Gwynedd in the Twelfth Century,'' which demolished Welsh claims of the [[discovery of the Americas]] by [[Madoc]], was acknowledged as the outstanding submission. However, although convincing, the essay was not awarded the prize due to the adjudicators' reluctance to discard the old claims. Disgusted, Stephens refused to compete in future eisteddfod competitions.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOther works include ''Orgraff yr Iaith Gymraeg'' (1859) (an orthography of Welsh), articles for ''[[Archaeologia Cambrensis]]'' and the [[South Wales]] newspapers and Welsh periodicals, essays on the life and works of the [[bard]] [[Aneirin|Aneurin]], and an English translation of ''[[Y Gododdin]].''<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe rigorous methods of literary criticism applied in his works often made Stephens unpopular with the less discriminating enthusiasts for the glory of Wales, but he earned the respect of serious scholars.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nStephens' manuscripts and letters are included in the [[National Library of Wales General Manuscript Collection]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://archives.library.wales/index.php/thomas-stephens-manuscripts-2|title=Fonds GB 0210 MSTOMSTP \u2013 Thomas Stephens Manuscripts|date=n.d.|website=National Library of Wales|url-status=live|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Davies|first=W. LL.|year=1939|title=The Thomas Stephens Manuscripts|url=http://welshjournals.llgc.org.uk/browse/viewpage/llgc-id:1277425/llgc-id:1277504/llgc-id:1277564/get650|journal=National Library of Wales Journal|volume=1|issue=2|page=96|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=National Library of Wales|title=Handlist of Manuscripts in the National Library of Wales, Volume I|date=1943|publisher=National Library of Wales|location=Aberystwyth}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Thomas_Stephens_(1821\u20131875)_bust.jpg|alt=|thumb|Bust of Thomas Stephens, {{Circa|1871}} by [[Joseph Edwards (sculptor)|Joseph Edwards]]. Presented to Stephens as a testimonial after 25 years as honorary secretary of the Merthyr Library.<ref name=\"Williams\"/>{{Rp|xlvi}}]]\n\n== Social reform ==\nWith the encouragement and friendship of [[Henry Bruce, 1st Baron Aberdare|Lord Aberdare]], Sir [[John Josiah Guest|Josiah John Guest]], and [[Lady Charlotte Guest]], Stephens was a prominent promoter of welfare, education and sanitary schemes in Merthyr Tydfil and organised relief for families of victims of coal mine explosions. He was appointed [[Constable#Historical usage|High Constable]] of Merthyr in 1858.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Legacy ==\nLiterary critic [[Meic Stephens]] states that Stephens \"is generally considered to have been the first Welsh literary critic to adopt a scientific method and to have done more, as an adjudicator, to raise the standards of the National Eisteddfod and to win for it the confidence of scholars, than any other Welshman of his time.\"<ref name=\":02\" />{{Rp|563}} However, he also notes the contrasting view presented by [[Emyr Humphreys]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Humphreys|first=Emyr|title=The Taliesin Tradition|publisher=Seren Books|year=2000|isbn=9781854112460|location=Bridgend}}</ref>\n\nStephens' modern biographer Marion L\u00f6ffler describes his \"main contributions to the shaping of Wales\" in terms of his work to transform Merthyr's social organisation and modernise Welsh culture, and \"his pioneering works of scholarship\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Works ==\n\n* {{cite book | title = History of the Life and Times of Iestyn ab Gwrgant, the Last Native Lord of Glamorgan | year  = 1840 | quote = eisteddfod essay | first = Thomas | last = Stephens}}\n* {{cite book | title = The Literature of Wales During the Twelfth and Succeeding Centuries  | year  = 1848 | quote = eisteddfod essay  | first = Thomas | last = Stephens}}\n* {{cite book | title = The Literature of the Kymry  | orig-year  = 1849  | edition = 2nd  | year  =  1876  | editor= Sylvan Evans  | first = Thomas | last = Stephens}}\n* {{cite book | title = Summary of the History of Wales from the Earliest Period to the Present Time  | year  = 1850 | quote = eisteddfod essay | first = Thomas | last = Stephens}}\n* {{cite book | title = Remains of the Welsh Poets from the Sixth Century to the Twelfth  | year  = 1853 | quote = eisteddfod essay | first = Thomas | last = Stephens}}\n* {{cite book | title = English Prose Translation of the \"Gododdin\" with Explanatory Notes | orig-year  = 1853  | year  = 1888 | quote = published as ''The Gododdin of Aneurin Gwawdrydd: An English Translation with Copious Explanatory Notes; A Life of Aneurin; and Several Lengthy Dissertations Illustrative of the \"Gododdin\", and the Battle of Cattraeth  | editor= Thomas Powel  | first = Thomas | last = Stephens}}\n* {{cite book | title = Madoc: An Essay on the Discovery of America by Madoc ap Owen Gwynedd in the Twelfth Century  | orig-year  = 1858 | quote = eisteddfod essay   | year  =  1893 | first = Thomas | last = Stephens}}\n* {{cite book | title = Orgraff yr Iaith Gymraeg | year = 1859 | first = Thomas | last = Stephens | author2 = Gweirydd ap Rhys (Robert John Pryse))}}\n\n* A series of critical essays, including:\n**{{cite journal | title = Edward Williams (Iolo Morganwg) (1852\u20131853) | journal = Yr Ymofynnydd |  first = Thomas | last = Stephens}}\n**{{cite journal | title = Dyfnwal Moelmud and Early Welsh Law | year = 1854 | journal = Cambrian Journal and Archaeologia Cambrensis | first = Thomas | last = Stephens}}\n**{{cite journal | title = The Book of Aberpergwm  | year = 1858 | journal = Archaeologia Cambrensis | first = Thomas | last = Stephens}}\n**{{cite journal | title = The Bardic Alphabet called \"Coelbren y Beirdd\"  | year = 1872 | journal = Archaeologia Cambrensis | first = Thomas | last = Stephens}}\n\n*Numerous shorter articles in newspapers such as ''[[The Cambrian]]'', ''The Merthyr Guardian'', ''The [[Monmouthshire Beacon|Monmouthshire Merlin]]'', and ''The Silurian,'' and in periodicals including ''[[Seren Gomer]]'', ''[[Yr Ymofynnydd]]'', ''[[Y Traethodydd]]'', and ''Y Beirniad.''\n\n(Sources for works: Dictionary of Welsh Biography<ref name=\":0\" />, National Library of Wales<ref name=\":1\" />, Stephens<ref name=\":02\" />, NLW Welsh newspapers<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newspapers.library.wales/home|title=Welsh Newspapers|last=|first=|date=|website=newspapers.library.wales|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref>)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External Sources ==\n{{wikisource author|Thomas Stephens}}\n{{commonscat|Thomas Stephens (historian)}}\n* {{cite news | url = https://newspapers.library.wales/view/4334011/4334017/50 | title = The Late Thomas Stephens | year = 1875}}\n* {{cite news | url = https://newspapers.library.wales/view/4334020/4334024/20  | title = The Late Thomas Stephens of Merthyr  | year = 1875}}\n* {{cite news | url = https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3500990/3500993/24  | title = Thomas Stephens  | year = 1875}}\n* [[iarchive:literatureofkymr00steprich/page/n25/mode/2up|The Life of Thomas Stephens. 1876.]]\n* [[iarchive:literatureofkymr00steprich/page/n56/mode/1up|A List of the Mss. Essays and Writings of Thomas Stephens. 1876.]]\n* [[iarchive:reddragon00unkngoog/page/n11/mode/2up|Notable Men of Wales. Thomas Stephens. 1882.]]\n* {{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3108130/3108140/25|title=Glamorgan|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live|year=1905}} (Portrait of Stephens once in Cardiff Reference Library)\n* {{cite news | url = https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3434011/3434016/12  | title = Mr Thos. Stephens. Distinguished Welsh Litterateur. Proposed Memorial  | year = 1908}}\n*[[iarchive:eminentwelshmens01robeuoft/page/500/mode/1up/|Stephens, Thomas. 1908.]] (Biography)\n*{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3435194/3435195/25|title=Welsh Gleanings|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live|year=1909}} (Connections with [[Joseph Edwards (sculptor)|Joseph Edwards]] and [[Charles Wilkins (writer)|Charles Wilkins]])\n* {{cite n